subsection.p:
The exponents of a polynomial can only be non-negative integers. That means functions like
          y = x^\frac{1}{2}
          and
          y = 2x^3 - x^{-5}
        are not polynomials.

image.latex-image-code:

\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ ,
  ymax=300, ymin=-300,
  xmax=4, xmin=-5, ytick={-300,-200,...,300}
  xlabel=$x$,ylabel=$f(x)$ ]
  \addplot[smooth, blue,
  domain=-5:4]
  {8*x^3+4*x^2-100*x+48};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}


\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ ,
  ymax=40, ymin=-40,
  xmax=6, xmin=-6,
  xlabel=$x$,ylabel=$y$ ]
  \addplot+[smooth, blue,
  domain=-5:4]
  {(x+3)^2*(x-1)};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

paragraphs.p:
The polynomials below both have (x+3)^2 as a factor, but they have other linear factors with either odd or even multiplicity:


              y = (x+3)^2(x-1)^2


                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-5:5]{(x+3)^2*(x-1)^2};
                                 \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}





              y = (x+3)^2(x-1)^2(x-4)


                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-5:5]{(x+3)^2*(x-1)^2*(x-4)};
                                 \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}

example.p:
If x was large, say 1,000,000, evaluating the function would look like:
            f(1,000,000) \amp= (1,000,000)^3 - 45(1,000,000)^2 + 12(1,000,000) - 20
            \amp= \text{ENORMOUS NUMBER} - \text{ HUGE Number } + \text{ Fairly Big Number } - \text{ small number }
            \amp= \text{Still an ENORMOUS NUMBER}
